The Graph Author was developed by Brendan Rousseau, a student at the TU/e. It is a high level DM/AM authoring tool that allows most authors to create their adaptive application without ever writing any AHA! rules, as seen in the [[concept-editor|concept editor]]. The tool generates these rules based on [[templates|template code]] associated with relations. Relations are drawn on the main screen between concepts. Relations also exist in the form of a concept hierarchy displayed on the left.
{{images/graphauthor.gif|The main screen of the graph author}}
The templates for concepts may specify user model updates that depend on the hierarchy. In a museum site a visit to a lower-level concept may indicate interest in the parent concept, and in a course such a visit may 'generate' knowledge of the parent concept. Concepts are dragged to the graph pane where they can be connected in any arbitrary way by concept relationships. The figure above shows a number of prerequisite relationships that cause link adaptation by checking the 'suitability' attribute of concepts. There are also some 'visibility' relationships that influence the presentation style for different fragments of text. The existence of adaptation rules is mostly invisible to authors using the Graph Author. Only in the adaptive resource selection for the conditional inclusion of objects and the adaptive link destinations do expressions over user model attributes become visible.
